<paragraph blockId="98.[151,1437,615,930]" pageId="98" pageNumber="99">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,305,615,642]" pageId="98" pageNumber="99">Distribution.</emphasis>
This species is recorded from the 
<collectingCountry box="[689,812,615,641]" name="Seychelles" pageId="98" pageNumber="99">Seychelles</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[823,935,615,641]" name="Mauritius" pageId="98" pageNumber="99">Mauritius</collectingCountry>
, throughout most of the Oriental Region, the northern part of 
<collectingCountry box="[332,435,651,677]" name="Australia" pageId="98" pageNumber="99">Australia</collectingCountry>
and few south west Pacific islands (
<bibRefCitation author="Tsuda, S." box="[840,976,651,678]" pageId="98" pageNumber="99" refId="ref36559" refString="Tsuda, S. (2000) A distributional list of world Odonata. Osaka, Japan, 430 pp." type="book" year="2000">Tsuda 2000</bibRefCitation>
). In 
<collectingCountry box="[1025,1201,651,678]" name="New Caledonia" pageId="98" pageNumber="99">New Caledonia</collectingCountry>
, it has been recorded as vagrant (
<bibRefCitation author="Davies, D. A. L." box="[283,429,687,714]" pageId="98" pageNumber="99" pagination="229 - 251" refId="ref31736" refString="Davies, D. A. L. (2002) The odonate fauna of New Caledonia, including the descriptions of a new species and a new subspecies. Odonatologica, 31, 229 - 251." type="journal article" year="2002">Davies 2002</bibRefCitation>
) at two locations in the south of Grande Terre, which are however not precisely known. Therefore, we did not map its distribution.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="98.[151,1437,615,930]" pageId="98" pageNumber="99">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,298,759,786]" pageId="98" pageNumber="99">Habitat.</emphasis>
We expect that this species in the same habitats as 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Fabricius" baseAuthorityYear="1798" box="[879,990,760,786]" class="Insecta" family="Libellulidae" genus="Tholymis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="98" pageNumber="99" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tillarga">
<emphasis box="[879,990,760,786]" italics="true" pageId="98" pageNumber="99">T. tillarga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but as it is also semi-crepuscular, fast- flying and less conspicuous it may be a more easily overlooked.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="98.[151,1437,615,930]" pageId="98" pageNumber="99">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,475,831,858]" pageId="98" pageNumber="99">Biology and behaviour.</emphasis>
The larva was illustrated by 
<bibRefCitation author="Lieftinck, M." box="[801,989,831,858]" pageId="98" pageNumber="99" pagination="1 - 95" refId="ref33740" refString="Lieftinck, M. (1962) Insects of Micronesia. Insects Micronesia, 5, 1 - 95." type="journal article" year="1962">Lieftinck (1962)</bibRefCitation>
. This is a migratory species most active towards dusk.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="98.[151,1437,615,930]" box="[199,1328,903,930]" pageId="98" pageNumber="99">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,281,903,930]" pageId="98" pageNumber="99">Status.</emphasis>
We considered this species as DD, because little information is available for 
<collectingCountry box="[1146,1323,903,930]" name="New Caledonia" pageId="98" pageNumber="99">New Caledonia</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
